 color=#6F6F6F>(3/19/02 8:11:58 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm10.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=17.topic>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.fas.org/nuke/hew/Usa/Tests/Rwmohawk2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://home.earthlink.net/~projectorion/ezboard/posticons/7.gif" align=absmiddle>  We Need Nuclear Radiation to Grow(children's level article).</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.etceteraweb.com/kids/sun.gif"><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br><br>The sun gives out radiation. You can see the light and you feel the heat -- especially on a summer's day at the beach, and if you are in the mountains both the light is brighter and the heat is warmer. <br><br><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.etceteraweb.com/kids/CO.jpg"><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br><br>And the sun gives out another type of radiation -- it's called ionizing radiation. That's a scientific name but we could call it nuclear radiation because it comes from inside the atom. Like the heat, you can't see it.<br><br>If the sun stopped giving light -- the world would be totally dark except for stars in the sky. If it stopped giving warmth, it would be disastrous. We'd be cold, very cold and nothing could grow. But what would happen if the sun stopped giving out nuclear radiation?<br>   <br>Some time ago, French researchers were also curious about the answer. They made an experiment. They took some small creatures (protozoa) in a saucer, and they surrounded the saucer by lead. <br><br>Just as a dark glass can stop light rays and insulation can stop heat rays, so a layer of lead can stop nuclear radiation. Thus, the protozoa could be deprived of nuclear radiation by putting one, two or three layers of thick lead over them.<br><br>First, the experimenters took notes on how the tiny animals grew. Then, they shielded them with the lead to reduce some nuclear rays, and then with more lead until no rays could get through. In that way they could tell what effect it would have if the sun stopped giving out nuclear radiation.<br>     <br>Well, they found that the tiny animals, the protozoa, didn't grow as well if they got less nuclear radiation, just as they would grew poorly with less light and warmth.<br><br>Very much later, other researchers found that without nuclear radiation, the tiny animals had less resistance to sickness (now we would call that a 'weaker immune system'). So they sickened from different types of illnesses and couldn't get well again.<br><br>So it turns out that we need the nuclear radiation from the sun.<br><br>What might happen, if someone shielded us by thick layers of lead? That experiement hasn't been done because humans take much longer to grow and show illnesses than tiny protozoa. But we can guess quite well.<br><br>We would guess, that our immune systems would also not develop as well and we might catch a disease. <br> <br>So when silly people tell you that any amount of radiation is bad for you remember to laugh in their faces and stick your tongue out.  <p>~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~<br>Nuclear power is the next logical step for serious space travel. The technology required to colonise the solar system exists now!<br><a href="http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace">NUCLEARSPACE</a></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uprojectorion.showPublicProfile?language=EN>projectorion</A> at: 3/19/02 8:20:37 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uyelmalio.showPublicProfile?language=EN>yelmalio</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Lurker</span><br>  Posts: 1<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(3/20/02 1:42:14 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm10.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=17.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://home.earthlink.net/~projectorion/ezboard/posticons/7.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: We Need Nuclear Radiation to Grow(children's level artic</span><hr size=1> Seems to me that if you totally shielded the Protozoa with lead no light or heat could get in either. That is a more likely cause for the demise of these creatures.<br><br>Using the above simplistic argument that radiation is good for you then more radiation is more good for you. Makes me wonder why I had to wear a radiation badge all those years in radiation labs playing with high energy sources. Damn that knee jerk reaction we had in Europe when Chernobyl blew. We should have basked in the energy giving glow of alpha radiation raining down on us. Give me radium waters or give me death.<br><br>Oh, and another thing, care to provide a cite for the above research? <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uyelmalio.showPublicProfile?language=EN>yelmalio</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Lurker</span><br>  Posts: 2<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(3/20/02 2:11:56 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm10.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=17.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://home.earthlink.net/~projectorion/ezboard/posticons/7.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: We Need Nuclear Radiation to Grow(children's level artic</span><hr size=1> Hmm, interesting<br><br>After doing a quick web search, as the above article gives little usefull information, I found that there is growing evidence for so called Radiation Hormesis. A prime researcher is one Richard T. Luckey. <br><br>To raise this above a childrens level, the argument is that extremely small amounts of a poisonous material can indeed stimulate the immune system or provide beneficial effects. Though radiation hormesis is not definitely proven there is growing evidence for it. But the researchers in this area are aware that large doses of ionising radiation, and non-ionising radiation, is definitely bad for you. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uprojectorion.showPublicProfile?language=EN>projectorion</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Nuclear Renaissance Man</span><br>  Posts: 737<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(3/20/02 2:20:31 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm10.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=17.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.fas.org/nuke/hew/Usa/Tests/Rwmohawk2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://home.earthlink.net/~projectorion/ezboard/posticons/7.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: We Need Nuclear Radiation to Grow(children's level artic</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Using the above simplistic argument that radiation is good for you then more radiation is more good for you. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br><br>As opposed to the other simplistic argument that large amounts of radiation are bad for you and therefore any level of radiation is bad for you?<br><br>Here's the source.<br><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.etceteraweb.com/kids/kids1.html">Kids Nuclear Science.</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br><br>Here's a couple more links aswell.<br><br><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.junkscience.com/news/lehr.html">Good News About Radon: The Linear Nonthreshold Model Is Wrong</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>Jay Lehr, Ph.D.<br>Environmental Education Enterprises<br>May 1996<br>The cancer risk from low-level radiation is normally estimated by use of a linear no-threshold theory which is a logical consequence of the view that a single particle of radiation hitting a single biological cell can initiate a cancer. The number of these initiating events would then be proportional to the number of particles of radiation and hence the dose. This theory however ignores the obvious biological defense mechanisms that prevent numerous initiating events from developing into cancers each day of our lives.<br><br><br><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.monadnock.net/fanspaces/hogan/truth_08.html">Radiation Good for Your Health?</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br><br>Imagine the consequences if the dogma upon which our policies for regulating and protecting against low-level ionizing radiation &amp;#8212; that &quot;no level is safe&quot;; any exposure however small, is damaging to health &amp;#8212; were shown to be incorrect. The hundreds of thousands of excess cancers predicted to occur eventually from Chernobyl could be consigned to the trash can. Practically the entire EPA industry for imposing standards and mandating cleanups involving low-level radiation would be closed down. A major weapon in the arsenal for the war on nuclear power would go away.<br><br>At levels encountered ordinarily &amp;#8212; i.e., excluding bomb victims, Chernobyl firefighters, and medical patients subjected to massive doses, usually as a last resort in terminal situations &amp;#8212; no conclusive results are actually observed at all. Low-level effects are inferred by taking a known high-level point where the effect is measurable, and assuming that it connects to the zero-point (zero dose, therefore zero effect) as a straight line. From this, one can read off the effects that low levels would have if this assumed relationship were true. This is like saying that since a temperature of 100Åã C is lethal, a rise however small must produce some ill effect. In the absence of better information, this can make sense for setting safety standards, where one prefers to err on the side of caution. But when it becomes interpreted as fact, the consequences can get out of hand.<br><br>**********************************************<br><br>All substances are poisons, there is none which is not a poison. The right dose differentiates a poison from a remedy.<br><br>All living organisms evolved and exist in a sea of ionizing radiation, much of which is internal. It is a general belief that low doses of ionizing radiation produce detrimental effects proportional to the effects produced by high-level radiation. In recent decades, however, some pioneering scientists have shown that low-dose ionizing radiation is not only a harmless agent but often has a beneficial or hormetic effect. That is, low-level ionizing radiation may be an essential trace energy for life, analogous to essential trace elements. It has been suggested that about one third of all cancer deaths are preventable by increasing our low dose radiation. <br><br><br><br> <p>~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~<br>Nuclear power is the next logical step for serious space travel. The technology required to colonise the solar system exists now!<br><a href="http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace">NUCLEARSPACE</a></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uprojectorion.showPublicProfile?language=EN>projectorion</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Nuclear Renaissance Man</span><br>  Posts: 738<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(3/20/02 2:33:49 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm10.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=17.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.fas.org/nuke/hew/Usa/Tests/Rwmohawk2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://home.earthlink.net/~projectorion/ezboard/posticons/7.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: We Need Nuclear Radiation to Grow(children's level artic</span><hr size=1> I forgot this one.<br><br><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.riskworld.com/Nreports/1999/jaworowski/NR99aa01.htm">Radiation Risk and Ethics</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br><br>by Zbigniew Jaworowski<br><br>(Reprinted with permission from Physics Today, 52(9), September 1999, pp. 24-29, American Institute of Physics.)<br><br>Extract.<br><br>In the regions of the former Soviet Union that were highly contaminated by the fallout from the Chernobyl accident, the increased radiation dose rate for local inhabitants is far less than the dose rate in areas of high natural radiation (see figure 2). In those places, the entire man-made contribution to radiation dose amounts to a mere 0.2% of the natural component. <br><br>Three and a half billion years ago, when life on Earth began, the natural level of ionizing radiation at the planetÅfs surface was about three to five times higher than it is now.6 Quite possibly, that radiation was needed to initiate life on Earth. And it may be essential to sustain extant life-forms, as suggested by experiments with protozoa and bacteria.7 <br><br>At the early stages of evolution, increasingly complex organisms developed powerful defense mechanisms against such adverse radiation effects as mutation and malignant change. Those effects originate in the cell nucleus, where the DNA is their primary target. That evolution has apparently proceeded for so long is proof, in part, of the effectiveness of living thingsÅf defenses against radiation. <br><br>Other adverse effects&amp;#8212;which lead to acute radiation sickness and premature death in humans&amp;#8212;also originate in the cell, but outside its nucleus. For them to take place requires radiation doses thousands of times higher than those from natural sources. A nuclear explosion or cyclotron beam could deliver such a dose; so could a defective medical or industrial radiation source. (The malfunctioning Chernobyl reactor, whose radiation claimed 28 lives, is one example.) <br><br>The concern abo